---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="BeaconGuard Assurance | Policy Control for AI-Assisted Regulated Workflows"
  description="BeaconGuard provides deterministic policy control and evidence capture before AI execution in regulated workflows, supporting compliance, privacy, security, risk, and audit review."
>
  <section class="landing">
    <p class="hero-eyebrow">Regulated AI Operations</p>
    <h1>Deterministic policy control for AI-assisted regulated workflows.</h1>
    <p>Control Before AI Execution. Evidence After Every Decision.</p>
    <p class="hero-subheadline">
      BeaconGuard inserts a policy and evidence boundary between enterprise applications and AI/model endpoints, returning explicit allow, deny, or needs-review decisions with preserved evidence for security, compliance, privacy, risk, and audit teams.
    </p>
    <p class="hero-subheadline">Sensitive requests are evaluated before AI or automation execution.</p>
    <div class="page-actions">
      <a class="btn-primary" href="/platform">Review the Platform</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/canonical-workflow">Explore Workflow Examples</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/proof-evidence">Review Proof &amp; Evidence</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/reviewer-kit">Open the Reviewer Kit</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Built for sensitive regulated operations</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard is built for workflows where AI or automation should not execute until policy has been checked.
      It keeps model behavior out of the authorization decision point and gives reviewers a standard record of what happened.
    </p>
    <p>
      The top-level control pattern applies across regulated enterprise operations. Financial crime, fraud, and dispute review remain valid
      examples, while healthcare privacy review, hospital operations support, and internal automation are also policy-gated workflow patterns.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Healthcare privacy and operational AI review</li>
      <li>Financial crime, fraud, and dispute review</li>
      <li>Internal automation touching regulated systems</li>
      <li>Customer-impacting account or service decisions</li>
      <li>Employee use of AI tools with sensitive data</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>What BeaconGuard controls</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      BeaconGuard is a runtime policy and evidence boundary for AI-assisted regulated workflows.
    </p>
    <p>
      It does not replace applications, models, clinical review, transaction systems, or compliance programs.
      It decides whether a request is permitted under explicit policy and returns deterministic outcomes with decision context for each event.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>What context can be sent to AI/model endpoints</li>
      <li>Which requests are allowed, denied, or routed for approval</li>
      <li>Which users, roles, workflows, or systems can trigger AI execution</li>
      <li>What evidence is preserved for later review</li>
      <li>What conditions require human approval</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Where BeaconGuard sits in the request path</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      A request enters BeaconGuard before model execution and only proceeds when policy is satisfied.
    </p>
    <p>Authorization logic is applied at runtime by a deterministic policy runtime, then returned as allow, deny, or needs-review plus decision metadata.</p>
    <p class="homepage-risk-framing">
      LLMs are probabilistic systems and should not be the authorization boundary for sensitive regulated workflows. BeaconGuard inserts deterministic policy control in the request path before model execution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <p class="section-label">Control boundary overview</p>
    <h2>Request control boundary</h2>
    <div class="infra-diagram home-boundary-diagram">
      <div class="flow-diagram flow-diagram--stack home-request-flow">
        <div class="flow-step flow-node-primary">
          <p class="flow-step-title">Enterprise Application</p>
          <p>Submits AI request with business context and authorization intent.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-node-boundary">
          <p class="flow-step-title">BeaconGuard Boundary</p>
          <p>Evaluates policy and returns deterministic allow, deny, or needs-review with reasons.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-node-evidence">
          <p class="flow-step-title">AI / Model Endpoint</p>
          <p>Receives the request only when policy permits execution.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-diagram flow-branch home-review-branch">
        <p class="flow-branch-title">Evidence &amp; review stream</p>
        <div class="flow-step flow-node-evidence flow-pulse">
          <p class="flow-step-title">Decision Record</p>
          <p>Decision context, policy identity, and outcome are emitted for audit and security review.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="flow-path-note">
      Decision outcomes are explicit and reviewable; execution occurs only after policy approval or approved review.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block home-boundary-section">
    <h2>Evidence and replay surface</h2>
    <div class="flow-diagram flow-diagram--stack home-evidence-flow">
      <div class="flow-step">
        <p class="flow-step-title">Application</p>
        <p>Submits request context and policy intent</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <p class="flow-step-title">BeaconGuard</p>
        <p>Evaluates policy with deterministic control</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <p class="flow-step-title">AI / Model Endpoint</p>
        <p>Executes only approved actions with trace metadata</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Every decision is reviewable with the same context used at evaluation time.</p>
  </section>

  <style>
    .home-boundary-section {
      overflow-wrap: anywhere;
      word-break: break-word;
    }

    .home-boundary-section .flow-path-note,
    .home-boundary-section .flow-branch-title,
    .home-boundary-section p {
      overflow-wrap: anywhere;
      word-break: break-word;
    }

    .home-boundary-section .flow-step {
      min-height: 0;
    }

    @media (max-width: 900px) {
      .home-request-flow,
      .home-evidence-flow {
        display: block;
        gap: 0;
      }

      .home-review-branch {
        display: block;
      }

      .home-request-flow .flow-step,
      .home-evidence-flow .flow-step {
        width: 100%;
        min-height: 0;
      }

      .home-request-flow .flow-arrow,
      .home-evidence-flow .flow-arrow {
        display: none;
      }

      .home-request-flow .flow-step + .flow-step,
      .home-evidence-flow .flow-step + .flow-step {
        margin-top: 1rem;
        position: relative;
        padding-top: 1.1rem;
      }

      .home-request-flow .flow-step + .flow-step::before,
      .home-evidence-flow .flow-step + .flow-step::before {
        content: "";
        position: absolute;
        left: 1rem;
        top: 0;
        width: 2px;
        height: 0.9rem;
        background: var(--brand-accent);
        transform: translateY(-65%);
      }

      .home-request-flow .flow-step + .flow-step::after,
      .home-evidence-flow .flow-step + .flow-step::after {
        content: "↓";
        position: absolute;
        left: 1rem;
        top: 0;
        transform: translate(-45%, -100%);
        font-size: 0.9rem;
        font-weight: 700;
        line-height: 1;
        color: var(--brand-accent);
      }

      .home-request-flow .flow-step,
      .home-evidence-flow .flow-step,
      .home-request-flow .flow-branch .flow-step {
        padding: 0.9rem 0.95rem;
        border-radius: 0.65rem;
      }

      .home-request-flow .flow-step-title,
      .home-evidence-flow .flow-step-title,
      .home-review-branch .flow-step-title {
        margin-bottom: 0.45rem;
      }
    }
  </style>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Workflow examples</h2>
    <div class="section-grid section-grid--compact">
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Healthcare AI Operations Review</h3>
        <p>Policy checks can detect PHI-sensitive context, require an approved AI pathway, route privacy review, or deny unapproved model endpoints before execution.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Financial Crime / Fraud Review</h3>
        <p>Analyst support, dispute review, AML, KYC, and fraud workflows can be gated so customer-impacting recommendations require policy approval and evidence.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Regulated Internal Automation</h3>
        <p>Automation touching regulated systems can be denied or routed for approval when role, change window, or action scope conditions are not met.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Failure handling and operational control</h2>
    <div class="homepage-failclosed-callout">
      <h3>Fail-closed control gate</h3>
      <p>
        If trust assumptions, policy conditions, or request context are missing, malformed, or out of bounds, BeaconGuard fails closed before the request reaches the model path.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-grid section-grid--compact">
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Fail-closed behavior</h3>
        <p>When policy context is malformed or incomplete, BeaconGuard defaults to deny and records the block condition.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Control assertions</h3>
        <p>Explicit allow, deny, and needs-review decisions remain reproducible and linked to policy identity and input context.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Replayability</h3>
        <p>Equivalent requests under the same policy state return equivalent outcomes for audit validation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Review readiness</h3>
        <p>Decision artifacts are structured for security, privacy, compliance, risk, and audit teams to reconstruct control behavior.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Deployment boundary and responsibility</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard is designed for controlled deployment postures where control decisions remain bounded at the policy layer and auditable by operational, compliance, privacy, security, and risk teams.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Deployment can be phased by policy domain and environment, without changing model behavior.</li>
      <li>Operational teams retain ownership of transaction execution workflows; BeaconGuard owns the control envelope.</li>
      <li>Decision outcomes are reviewable independently from the model implementation path.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Trust and review surface</h2>
    <p>Risk, security, privacy, compliance, and audit stakeholders can use BeaconGuard as the review layer for runtime controls.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Decision context and outcomes are explicit and reproducible.</li>
      <li>Evidence is preserved for investigation and controls testing.</li>
      <li>Control behavior can be reviewed without exposing model internals.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted-copy">
      Review teams consume the same decision context needed for audit-ready governance.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Design partner review path</h2>
    <div class="stack-callout">
      <p>Design partners help validate policy boundaries, fail-closed behavior, and evidence requirements before production rollout.</p>
      <p><a href="/design-partner-program">Learn how we run design partner evaluations</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section homepage-block">
    <h2>Get Started</h2>
    <p>
      Start with the architecture and move into workflow examples, deployment boundaries, and review planning.
    </p>
    <div class="page-actions">
      <a class="btn-primary" href="/platform">Review the Platform</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/canonical-workflow">Explore Workflow Examples</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/trust-assurance">Trust Center</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/deployment">Review deployment boundary</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>